                     HEDIT v1.05 Technical Reference
                   CP/M 2.2 Hex Editor for the IMSAI 8080
                   =======================================


    1. PROJECT OVERVIEW

    HEDIT is a full-screen hex editor written in Intel 8080 assembly
    language for CP/M 2.2.  It uses a gap buffer data structure for
    efficient insertion and deletion, link-time module substitution
    to support four terminal families, and supports both raw binary
    and Intel HEX file formats.

    Target platform:  IMSAI 8080 with CP/M 2.2
    CPU:              Intel 8080 (no Z80 instructions)
    Terminals:        VT100 / ANSI, DEC VT52, Lear Siegler ADM-31,
                      Cromemco 3102 (Beehive DM10 / DM30)
    Assembler:        Microsoft M80 (Macro-80)
    Linker:           Microsoft L80


    2. VARIANTS

    HEDIT builds as five separate .COM files.  Each one links the
    core modules against a different screen-driver / key-input /
    menu trio.  All trios export the same PUBLIC symbols so the
    rest of the program is terminal-agnostic.

       Binary          COLOR   Screen    Keys       Menu
       --------------  ------  --------  ---------  --------
       HEDIT.COM       0       HEXSCR    HEXKEY     HEXMENU
       HEDIT-CL.COM    1       HEXSCR    HEXKEY     HEXMENU
       HEDIT-52.COM    0       HEVT52    HEXKEY     HEXMNVT
       HEDIT-AD.COM    0       HEADM31   HEADM31K   HEXMNVT
       HEDIT-CR.COM    0       HEC3102   HEC3102K   HEXMNVT

    The COLOR flag is read by HEXSCR from HECONFIG.INC at assembly
    time and has no effect on any other screen driver.  HEPATCH
    (CP/M side) or HEBUILD.PY (host side) rewrites the flag between
    the mono and colour VT100 builds.


    3. SOURCE FILES

    Shared modules (all variants):
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    File            Purpose                Key Exports
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    HEDIT.MAC       Entry point, main      INSMODE, DIRTY, DRTLINE,
                    loop, action dispatch, CURBDP, TPATOP, DOEXIT,
                    runtime dimensions     EDITMODE, NIBBLE,
                                           REROWS, RSEPR, RSTAT,
                                           RBYTPG
    HEDIT.INC       Shared equates         (INCLUDE-only)
    HECONFIG.INC    Compile-time config    (INCLUDE-only, COLOR)
    HEXGAP.MAC      Gap buffer engine      GBINIT, GBINSRT, GBDLFT,
                                           GBDELRT, GBMVLT, GBMVRT,
                                           GBMVTP, GBMVEND, GBMVTO,
                                           GBRDBLK, GBLOGRD, GBTXEND,
                                           GBCSOFF, GBGAPBG, GBGAPEN
    HEXIO.MAC       File load/save,        FIOPEN, FISAVE, FIPROMPT,
                    Intel HEX parser       FISAVFN, FISMOD, WRKFCB
    HEXSRCH.MAC     Hex and ASCII search   SRFIND, SRFNDNX
    HEXBLK.MAC      Block mark, copy,      BLMARK, BLCOPY, BLDEL,
                    delete, paste          BLPASTE
    HEXKBND.MAC     Key binding init from  KBINIT
                    HEDIT.KEY
    HEXVIRT.MAC     Virtual buffer I/O     VIMODE, VISAVALL, VIGOTO
    HEXHELP.MAC     Help screen overlay,   HLPSHOW, BMDATEND
                    BMDATEND marker

    Terminal-specific screen drivers (one per variant):
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    File            Terminal               Notes
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    HEXSCR.MAC      VT100 / ANSI           Full colour / DSR / SGR
    HEVT52.MAC      DEC VT52               ESC Y addressing
    HEADM31.MAC     Lear Siegler ADM-31    ESC = addressing
    HEC3102.MAC     Cromemco 3102          ESC F addressing

    All four export the same public surface:
       SCRINIT, SCRDRAW, SCREDCL, INFOBAR, CURPOS, STATMSG, STATCLR,
       OUTCHAR, OUTSTR, CURGOTO, OUTN4HX, OUTN2HX, ISLOAD, DETSIZ,
       ATTRON, ATROFF, CLRTOE

    Terminal-specific key modules:
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    File            Used by                Notes
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    HEXKEY.MAC      VT100, VT52            Standard VT100 CSI / SS3
                                           decoder
    HEADM31K.MAC    ADM-31                 Structurally identical
                                           to HEXKEY; separate fork
                                           documents raw-arrow
                                           conflict with WordStar
    HEC3102K.MAC    Cromemco 3102          HEXKEY + ESC+letter
                                           fallback so native
                                           ESC A/B/C/D arrow keys
                                           hit the same CSITBL
                                           entries as VT100 ESC[A

    Menu modules:
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    File            Used by                Notes
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    HEXMENU.MAC     VT100 mono, VT100      Embeds ANSI SGR bold for
                    colour                 shortcut-letter emphasis
    HEXMNVT.MAC     VT52, ADM-31, C3102    Plain-text shortcut
                                           letters; imports ATTRON
                                           / ATROFF from the active
                                           screen driver for reverse
                                           video

    Tools and build scripts:
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    File            Purpose
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    HEPATCH.MAC     Standalone CP/M-side patcher that rewrites
                    COLOR EQU in HECONFIG.INC.  Built by M80/L80
                    into HEPATCH.COM; invoked by every per-variant
                    .SUB as the first step.
    HEBUILD.PY      Host-side equivalent of HEPATCH for the
                    build-all.bat flow.
    CPMFMT.PY       Normalises .MAC / .INC / .SUB files to CR+LF
                    line endings and appends a Ctrl-Z EOF marker
                    for .MAC and .SUB (not .INC, which M80 INCLUDE
                    must be able to return from).
    build-all.bat   Windows / cpmulator build of all five variants.
    HEDIT.SUB,
    HEDIT-CL.SUB,
    HEDIT-52.SUB,
    HEDIT-AD.SUB,
    HEDIT-CR.SUB   Self-contained CP/M-side per-variant builds.
    HEPATCH.SUB     Build just HEPATCH.COM.
    CLEAN.SUB       Delete *.REL and TEMP.COM.

    IMPORTANT: HEXHELP.MAC must be linked LAST.  BMDATEND is
    computed by L80 at the end of HEXHELP's CSEG and marks the
    bottom of the gap buffer.


    4. BUILD PROCESS

    M80 processes INCLUDE directives natively, so CPMFMT.PY only
    normalises line endings and EOF markers; it no longer inlines
    .INC files into .MAC files.

    Step 1: Normalise sources

      python CPMFMT.PY

    Or on CP/M, just keep source files in CP/M format (CR+LF plus
    Ctrl-Z on .MAC / .SUB).

    Step 2: Set the COLOR flag (VT100 builds only)

      Host:  python HEBUILD.PY 0   (mono)
             python HEBUILD.PY 1   (colour)
      CP/M:  HEPATCH 0   (mono)
             HEPATCH 1   (colour)

    Non-VT100 variants do not read COLOR; the step is still run in
    each .SUB so the source tree is left in a known state.

    Step 3: Assemble the modules this variant needs

      Shared:     HEDIT HEXGAP HEXIO HEXSRCH HEXBLK HEXKBND
                  HEXVIRT HEXHELP
      VT100:      +HEXSCR HEXKEY HEXMENU
      VT52:       +HEVT52 HEXKEY HEXMNVT
      ADM-31:     +HEADM31 HEADM31K HEXMNVT
      C3102:      +HEC3102 HEC3102K HEXMNVT

    Each M80 =MODULE produces MODULE.REL.

    Step 4: Link

      VT100:   L80 HEDIT,HEXSCR,HEXKEY,HEXGAP,HEXIO,HEXMENU,
                   HEXSRCH,HEXBLK,HEXKBND,HEXVIRT,HEXHELP,
                   HEDIT/N/E
      VT52:    L80 HEDIT,HEVT52,HEXKEY,HEXGAP,HEXIO,HEXMNVT,
                   HEXSRCH,HEXBLK,HEXKBND,HEXVIRT,HEXHELP,
                   HEDIT-52/N/E
      ADM-31:  L80 HEDIT,HEADM31,HEADM31K,HEXGAP,HEXIO,HEXMNVT,
                   HEXSRCH,HEXBLK,HEXKBND,HEXVIRT,HEXHELP,
                   HEDIT-AD/N/E
      C3102:   L80 HEDIT,HEC3102,HEC3102K,HEXGAP,HEXIO,HEXMNVT,
                   HEXSRCH,HEXBLK,HEXKBND,HEXVIRT,HEXHELP,
                   HEDIT-CR/N/E

    /N suppresses the symbol-table listing.  /E exits L80 after
    writing the .COM file.

    The per-variant .SUB files (SUBMIT HEDIT, SUBMIT HEDIT-CL,
    etc.) automate this whole sequence, linking to TEMP.COM and
    renaming the result.


    5. MEMORY MAP

      0000h         CP/M warm boot vector
      0005h         BDOS entry point
      005Ch         Default FCB (command line filename)
      0080h         Command tail / DMA buffer
      0100h         TPA start -- HEDIT.COM loads here
      ....          CSEG code + read-only data
                    DSEG mutable variables
      BMDATEND      End of static data (defined in HEXHELP.MAC)
      BMDATEND..    Gap buffer (all remaining TPA memory)
      ..BDOS-1      Top of gap buffer
      BDOS          BDOS handler

    Minimum free memory (BMDATEND to BDOS, i.e. the gap buffer
    region): 9 KB (MINMEM = 9*1024).  HEDIT refuses to start if
    (TPATOP - BMDATEND) is smaller than this.  This is *not* the
    total TPA; the full HEDIT.COM binary and its static data sit
    below BMDATEND and do not count toward the 9 KB.


    6. GAP BUFFER ARCHITECTURE

    HEDIT uses a gap buffer for the edit data.  The buffer occupies
    all free memory from BMDATEND to the top of TPA.

      Memory layout:
        [R1: pre-gap data] [---GAP---] [R2: post-gap data]
        base               GAPBG       GAPEN               base+BSIZE

    The cursor position is always at the gap boundary.  Inserting a
    byte writes it at GAPBG and advances GAPBG.  Deleting removes a
    byte by moving the gap boundary.

    Moving the cursor bulk-copies bytes across the gap:
      - Move right: copy bytes from R2 start to R1 end (forward)
      - Move left:  copy bytes from R1 end to R2 start (backward)

    Gap buffer is purely byte-oriented -- no line delimiters, no LF
    counting.  Navigation is by byte offset:
      - Left/right: +/- 1 byte
      - Up/down:    +/- 16 bytes
      - Page:       +/- RBYTPG bytes (see section 8)


    7. BUFFER DESCRIPTOR

    Each buffer is described by a 34-byte descriptor (BD_SIZE = 34):

      Offset  Size  Field       Description
      ------  ----  ----------  ----------------------------------
       0      2     BD_BSTAR    Buffer base address in RAM
       2      2     BD_BSIZE    Buffer capacity in bytes
       4      2     BD_GAPBG    Gap start offset (relative to base)
       6      2     BD_GAPEN    Gap end offset (relative to base)
       8      2     BD_TXEND    Logical data length (R1 + R2 size)
      10      2     BD_TOPOFF   Top visible byte offset (16-aligned)
      12      2     BD_CSOFF    Cursor byte offset
      14      2     BD_MRKBG    Block mark start (FFFFh = unset)
      16      2     BD_MRKEN    Block mark end (FFFFh = unset)
      18      1     BD_MODIF    Modified flag (0 clean, 1 dirty)
      19      1     BD_FILEFMT  File format (0 binary, 1 Intel HEX)
      20      12    BD_FNAME    Drive (1) + name (8) + ext (3)
      32      2     BD_BADDR    Intel HEX base address

    CURBDP is a global pointer to the active buffer descriptor.


    8. RUNTIME SCREEN DIMENSIONS

    The EQU constants EDITROW / SEPRROW / STATROW / BYTESPG in
    HEDIT.INC give the compile-time defaults for a 24-row terminal.
    They initialise four runtime variables in HEDIT.MAC's DSEG that
    the rest of the program reads at run time:

      REROWS   DB  EDITROW  hex-area row count       (default 20)
      RSEPR    DB  SEPRROW  separator row            (default 23)
      RSTAT    DB  STATROW  status / prompt row      (default 24)
      RBYTPG   DW  BYTESPG  bytes per page           (default 320)

    These are the PUBLIC symbols that every screen driver and
    every module with status-bar output pulls in via EXTRN.  Page
    navigation, scroll alignment, SCRDRAW's row loop, and every
    "position cursor on row N" site all read from these variables.

    A helper routine BPG16 in HEDIT.MAC returns DE = RBYTPG - 16
    (used twice in CHKSCRL / CSBELOW for scroll alignment),
    preserving HL.  If RBYTPG changes at run time, BPG16 stays
    consistent because it re-reads RBYTPG each call.


    9. DETSIZ -- TERMINAL ROW AUTO-DETECT

    DETSIZ is called from HEDIT.MAC's startup, just before SCRINIT.
    On the VT100 screen driver (HEXSCR.MAC) it queries the terminal
    and rewrites the runtime dimension variables:

      1. Save cursor           ESC 7
      2. Move to far corner    ESC [ 9 9 9 ; 9 9 9 H
      3. Request position      ESC [ 6 n
      4. Collect CPR response  ESC [ rows ; cols R
         into DSCPBUF with an inter-byte timeout loop
      5. Restore cursor        ESC 8
      6. Parse rows, clamp to [24, 76]
      7. RSTAT  = rows
         RSEPR  = rows - 1
         REROWS = rows - 4        (info bar + header + sep + stat)
         RBYTPG = REROWS * 16

    On parse failure or DSR timeout, the cursor is restored and the
    compile-time 24-row defaults remain in place.  The upper clamp
    (76) matches TeraTerm's tallest practical layout on a 4K
    monitor at its smallest font.

    The VT52, ADM-31 and Cromemco 3102 screen drivers implement
    DETSIZ as a bare RET; none of those protocols define a DSR
    response, so the 24-row defaults always hold on those builds.


    10. SCREEN LAYOUT

    The display is organized as follows (N = RSTAT = terminal rows):

      Row 1:       Info bar (filename, size, offset, mode flags)
      Row 2:       Column header (dim text)
      Rows 3..N-2: Hex data area (REROWS rows, 16 bytes each)
      Row N-1:     Separator line (version string + '=' fill)
      Row N:       Status/message bar

    Data row format (72 visible characters):
      Col  1-4:   Hex address (4 digits, 0000-FFFF)
      Col  5-6:   ": " separator
      Col  7-30:  First 8 hex bytes ("XX XX XX XX XX XX XX XX")
      Col 31:     Group separator space
      Col 32-55:  Second 8 hex bytes ("XX XX XX XX XX XX XX XX")
      Col 56-57:  Gap (2 spaces)
      Col 58-73:  16 ASCII characters (20h-7Eh shown, else '.')

    Colour scheme (VT100 colour variant only):
      Address field:  Bold green
      Hex bytes:      Cyan
      ASCII field:    Yellow
      Column header:  Dim
      Separator:      Dim
      Info bar:       Reverse video
      Block marks:    Reverse video

    In the VT100 mono variant (COLOR=0), bold / dim / reverse are
    still available; only colour SGR codes are replaced with
    attribute resets.

    The VT52 / ADM-31 / C3102 screen drivers replace the bold / dim /
    colour SGR strings with empty "$" strings.  The shared rendering
    code keeps calling OUTSTR on those labels without visible effect.
    Reverse video still works via each driver's native sequence
    (ESC p / ESC q on VT52 clones, ESC G 4 / ESC G 0 on ADM-31,
    ESC d P / ESC d @ on C3102).


    11. SELECTIVE REDRAW SYSTEM

    The main loop uses a two-level dirty flag system:

      DIRTY    DRTLINE   Action
      -----    -------   -----------------------------------------
        1        *       SCRDRAW: full redraw (REROWS rows)
                         + header + separator
        0        1       SCREDCL: current row only
        0        0       No content redraw (cursor-only move)

    INFOBAR and CURPOS always run at MLDONE regardless of flags.

    During block marking (MRKBG set, MRKEN = FFFFh), DIRTY is forced
    to 1 every iteration so the live highlight preview tracks the
    cursor.

    Block-mark highlighting is optimised: per-row highlight bounds
    (SHHLS, SHHLE) are precomputed by SHHLRNG, and attribute
    changes are emitted only at transition points.


    12. KEY INPUT SYSTEM

    The key decoder (HEXKEY, HEADM31K, HEC3102K) is a state machine.

      State       Description
      ---------   --------------------------------
      KST_IDL     Idle, no prefix received
      KST_ESC     Received ESC (0x1B)
      KST_CSI     Received ESC [ (CSI)
      KST_SS3     Received ESC O (SS3)
      KST_CSP     CSI with parameter digits
      KST_CTK     Ctrl-K prefix active
      KST_CTQ     Ctrl-Q prefix active

    GETKEY returns:
      B = key type (KT_NONE, KT_ACT, or KT_CHAR)
      C = action code or character value

    Dispatch tables (all three key modules export these):
      KBDTBL   Ctrl codes 0-31 -> action codes (32 bytes)
      CSITBL   (final_byte, param, action) triples, NUL-terminated
      SS3TBL   (final_byte, action) pairs
      CTKTBL   Ctrl-K prefix: (char, action) pairs
      CTQTBL   Ctrl-Q prefix: (char, action) pairs

    HEC3102K extends GKESC2 with an ESC+letter fallback: after ESC,
    any A-Z byte that is not '[' or 'O' is treated as a CSI with
    param=0 and looked up in CSITBL.  This lets both native C3102
    arrows (ESC A/B/C/D) and VT100 emulation (ESC [ A/B/C/D) hit
    the same table entries.


    13. FILE I/O

    Binary files:
      Load: read 128-byte records via BF_FREAD, insert each byte
            via GBINSRT, stop when BF_FREAD returns non-zero.
            All byte values including 1Ah are loaded.
      Save: read logical bytes via GBLOGRD, write 128-byte records
            via BF_FWRITE, pad final record with zeros.

    Intel HEX files:
      Load: auto-detected when first byte is ':' (3Ah).  Parsed
            record by record via IHRDLN / IHPARS.  Base address is
            captured from the first data record.  Address gaps
            between records are filled with FFh.  Type 02/04
            extended address records show an error and are skipped.
      Save: 16-byte data records with checksums, addresses include
            BD_BADDR, terminated with an EOF record (:00000001FF).

    Save creates a .BAK backup by renaming the existing file before
    writing the new version.


    14. SEARCH ENGINE

    HEXSRCH.MAC provides forward search with wrap-around.

    Two search types:
      Hex:   space-separated hex byte pairs ("4D 5A 90 00")
      ASCII: literal text string

    Algorithm:
      1. Start at CSOFF + 1 (one past cursor)
      2. At each position, try matching SRCHBUF[0..SRCHLEN-1]
         against logical data via GBLOGRD
      3. If end of data reached, wrap to offset 0
      4. Stop on match or full circle

    Maximum search pattern: 64 bytes (SRCHMAX).


    15. BLOCK OPERATIONS

    Block marks live in BD_MRKBG and BD_MRKEN.  Both are FFFFh when
    no mark is active.

    Mark state machine:
      Both FFFFh          -> MRKBG = cursor,  MRKEN = FFFFh
      MRKBG set, MRKEN=FF -> MRKEN = cursor (swap if needed)
      Both set            -> clear both to FFFFh

    Copy: reads MRKBG..MRKEN into CLPBUF via GBLOGRD.  Maximum
          clipboard: 2048 bytes (CLIPMAX).
    Delete: moves cursor to MRKBG, calls GBDELRT for the length.
    Paste: inserts CLPLEN bytes from CLPBUF at cursor via GBINSRT.


    16. HEPATCH -- CP/M-SIDE CONFIG PATCHER

    HEPATCH.COM is a small standalone CP/M utility that rewrites
    the COLOR EQU value in HECONFIG.INC.  It lets the per-variant
    .SUB files set the compile-time configuration on real CP/M
    without requiring Python.

    Usage:
      HEPATCH 0    set COLOR = 0 (mono)
      HEPATCH 1    set COLOR = 1 (colour)

    Implementation:
      1. Open HECONFIG.INC, read one record (file is < 128 bytes)
         into FBUF via BF_FREAD.
      2. Scan FBUF for the NUL-terminated pattern "COLOR   EQU".
      3. Skip spaces/tabs after EQU, overwrite the first byte
         with the ASCII digit.
      4. Delete and recreate the file, write FBUF as one record.

    A generic PATCH subroutine accepts (pattern, digit) and can be
    invoked multiple times.  Adding a future EQU is a 4-line
    change: new NUL-terminated pattern, an extra arg parse, one
    more CALL PATCH.


    17. CODING CONVENTIONS

    - Intel 8080 assembly ONLY.  No Z80 instructions.
    - BDOS calls clobber ALL registers.  Any value needed across a
      CALL BDOS must be saved to memory or stack.
    - M80 truncates symbols to 6 characters.  Avoid symbols that
      differ only after the 6th character.
    - After every .MAC / .INC / .SUB edit, run CPMFMT.PY.
    - CSEG for code and read-only data; DSEG for mutable variables.
    - No ORG 100H in CSEG for .COM-file sources; rely on
      CSEG + END START so L80 generates the JMP at 0100H.
      (ORG 100H in CSEG without a preceding ASEG creates a
      gap that inherits the previous M80 run's TPA on real CP/M.)


    18. DEPENDENCIES BETWEEN MODULES

    HEDIT.MAC     imports symbols from every other module.  Exports
                  CURBDP, DIRTY, DRTLINE, INSMODE, EDITMODE, NIBBLE,
                  TPATOP, DOEXIT, and the four runtime dimension
                  variables REROWS / RSEPR / RSTAT / RBYTPG.
    HEXSCR.MAC    imports CURBDP, DIRTY, INSMODE, EDITMODE, NIBBLE,
                  GBRDBLK, GBTXEND, GBCSOFF, plus the runtime dim
                  variables.
    HEVT52,       same interface as HEXSCR; imports the same set.
    HEADM31,
    HEC3102.MAC
    HEXKEY.MAC    imports only HEDIT.INC constants.
    HEADM31K.MAC  same as HEXKEY (identical code).
    HEC3102K.MAC  same as HEXKEY + ESC+letter fallback code.
    HEXGAP.MAC    imports CURBDP.
    HEXIO.MAC     imports CURBDP, ISLOAD, GBINIT, GBINSRT, GBMVTP,
                  GBTXEND, GBBASE, GBBSIZ, GBGAPBG, GBGAPEN, GBLOGRD,
                  STATMSG, OUTSTR, OUTCHAR, CURGOTO, INFOBAR, RSTAT.
    HEXMENU.MAC   imports GETKEY, CURBDP, DIRTY, INSMODE, EDITMODE,
                  FIOPEN, FISAVE, FIPROMPT, FISAVFN, FISMOD, STATMSG,
                  OUTSTR, OUTCHAR, CURGOTO, INFOBAR, SCRDRAW,
                  GBMVTO, GBTXEND, GBCSOFF, GBINSRT, GBDELRT,
                  SRFIND, HLPSHOW, DOEXIT, RSTAT.
    HEXMNVT.MAC   same as HEXMENU + EXTRN ATTRON / ATROFF from the
                  active screen driver (replaces local ANSI SGR).
    HEXSRCH.MAC   imports CURBDP, DIRTY, GBLOGRD, GBTXEND, GBCSOFF,
                  GBMVTO, STATMSG, STATCLR, OUTSTR, OUTCHAR, CURGOTO,
                  RSTAT.
    HEXBLK.MAC    imports CURBDP, DIRTY, GBINSRT, GBDLFT, GBDELRT,
                  GBMVTO, GBCSOFF, GBLOGRD, GBTXEND, STATMSG.
    HEXKBND.MAC   imports KBDTBL, CSITBL, SS3TBL, CTKTBL, CTQTBL,
                  STATMSG, OUTSTR.
    HEXVIRT.MAC   imports CURBDP, DIRTY, GBINIT, GBMVTP, GBBASE,
                  GBBSIZ, GBGAPEN, GBCSOFF, GBLOGRD, GBTXEND,
                  SCRDRAW, INFOBAR, CURPOS, STATMSG, WRKFCB.
    HEXHELP.MAC   imports OUTSTR, OUTCHAR, CURGOTO, DIRTY, ATTRON,
                  ATROFF, CLRTOE, SCRINIT, RSTAT.
    HEPATCH.MAC   standalone .COM; no EXTRNs.
